X202001.text_comments: Obv. 12: né-hi "slow, quiet" is said of rain and thunder in the diaries; neither of these is expressed by the sign NIM. NIM could be an abbreviation of NIM.GÍR "lightning", but this is usually abbreviated to GÍR. Rev. 6-9: these lines were scratched on the tablet when the clay was almost dry, and are only lightly impressed.

X202011.date_comments: The date can be established from a second stationary point of Saturn next to ρ Leonis on the 12th (l. 13'), and from the position of Jupiter 1 ½ cubits east of the moon on the same night (l. 12'). This fits best SE 110, which is confirmed by lunar data. Venus can then be restored in l. 5'.

X202012.date_comments: The month is given on the tablet. An acronychal rising of Sirius on X 14  (rev 9)allows identification of the year modulo 19; a first stationary point of Saturn on X 4 (obv. 5) and a first appearance of Mercury in the east on X 13 (rev. 5) fix the year as SE 110. The remaining observations confirm this.

X202013.date_comments: The month is noted on the tablet; the year number is not specified. The suggested date SE 110 results from a consideration of the following points: (a) short diaries of this kind do not occur before the beginning of the Seleucid period; (b) month XII2, sunset to moonset on the 1st evening: 19°; (c) the same evening, the moon was ½ cubit in front of Mercury, the moon being 1 cubit low to the south. An investigation of all months XII2 from SE 1 to 300, requiring that the moon be near Mercury and that the interval from sunset to moonset be close to 19°, eliminates all possibilities except SE 110 and 137. The date SE 110 is to be preferred because of the lunar data for that year in a Goal-year text listed as LBAT *1244f. rev. 4: [D]IR.ŠE 1 19 na-su KUR4 a-pir muš.

X202014.date_comments: The year can be found by: (a) a solar eclipse which was omitted (obv. 6); (b) an acronychal rising of Jupiter on XII2 30 (obv. 8); (c) Mars next to δ Cancri on XII2 28 (obv. 2). Lunar data agree with SE 110 thus found.

X202022.date_comments: The date can be found from the planetary statements in obv. 9' and rev. 4'

X202030.text_comments: Lower edge: is the last sign na an abbreviation for nalšu?

X202042.date_comments: The date can be found from the positions of Mars above γ Geminorum on the 15th (obv. 4') and of Venus next to η and μ Geminorum on the 17th and [19th] of the same month, in combination with several lunar positions. It is confirmed by the duplicate BM 35424 (below C).

X202043.tablet_comments: This tablet is badly preserved. Only a few lines can be read on the obverse; even these are uncertain.
X202043.date_comments: The mention of a king Antiochus shows the text to be from the Seleucid era. The date can then be found by means of the planetary statements in rev. 9f.

X202071.tablet_comments: Both pieces are part of the same tablet and form a touch join.
X202071.date_comments: The one line preserved of the reverse shows that the diary refers to a time when a king reigned together with his son whose name was Antiochus; this was the case only in years SE 46-51, 102-119, 123-125, and 137-142. Planetary observations, especially Jupiter in Aries, and a last appearance of Saturn on the 5th of the second month, permit to identify the year as SE 104.

X202072.date_comments: The phrase "were sold in the land" in price statements occurs for the first time in a dated text from SE 64; the fragment therefore should date to the Seleucid era. It can then be assigned to SE 104 from the positions of Jupiter and Venus in line 6', combined with a stationary point of some planet close to η or μ Geminorum towards the end of the month (l. 4') and the position of the moon next to Mercury (l. 3'). The date of this text was found by F. R. Stephenson.

X202080.date_comments: The following data can be used: (a) Saturn was in Taurus; (b) Jupiter’s acronychal rising occurred on the 22nd; (c) Mercury’s last appearance in the west in Virgo. The only date during the Seleucid era which fulfills these conditions is SE 103 V. The few lunar positions recorded agree with this date.

X202091.tablet_comments: The five exemplars available for this year show little overlap and are therefore presented in chronological order. 209A may be part of the same tablet as exemplar D.
X202091.date_comments: The tablet refers to a year in which a king Antiochus ruled. According to the lunar positions, and because the text is from the beginning of the obverse, the month must have been I. A conjunction of Venus and Saturn on the first day of this month (obv. 1) suffices to establish the date.

X202092.tablet_comments: The five exemplars available for this year show little overlap and are therefore presented in chronological order. 209A may be part of the same tablet as exemplar D.
X202092.date_comments: The date is based on: (a) a last appearance of Saturn on the 6th or 7th of a month (l. 4'); (b) Jupiter in Aquarius (l. 14'); (c) a lunar eclipse not visible in Babylon (l. 7').

X202093.tablet_comments: The five exemplars available for this year show little overlap and are therefore presented in chronological order. 209A may be part of the same tablet as exemplar D.
X202093.date_comments: On the 22nd of a month, a first appearance of Saturn occurred in the beginning of Taurus (rev. 2). On the 10th, Mars, being retrograde, was above δ Scorpii (obv. 6'). The date SE 102 II resulting from these observations is confirmed by the positions of Venus and Mercury (obv. 3' and 5').

X202094.tablet_comments: This may be part of the same tablet as exemplar A.
X202094.copy: Listed as LBAT *299 and *300. Copy (by T.G.Pinches): plate 104f. (BM 45608)
X202094.text_comments: Obv. 17': ι Aquarii would be in the position required by the description of Jupiter's stationary point.
X202094.date_comments: The date is easily established by several planetary positions.

X202095.tablet_comments: The five exemplars available for this year show little overlap and are therefore presented in chronological order. 209A may be part of the same tablet as exemplar D.

X202100.date_comments: On the 9th of a month which was V or VI according to the positions of the moon. Mars was above ρ Leonis (rev. 11'). On the 27th of the preceding month, Venus was 2 fingers above α Leonis (rev. 6'); on the 18th (restored with certainty from other lunar positions) of this month, Saturn was somewhat more than 3 cubits west of α Arietis. This is sufficient to establish the date. The months of the obverse are then easily identified.

X202111.date_comments: A king Antiochus is mentioned on the upper edge; therefore, only years 32-66, 90-125, 137-151, and 182-183 of the Seleucid era are possible. From the dates of the lunar positions it follows that the month must be VI or VII. Between the 3rd and the 7th, Jupiter was above θ Ophiuchi in the first part of the night; on the same evening, the moon was 5 fingers below Mars (obv. 2). From these observations, the date can be identified as SE 100, month VI. The remaining lunar observations, as well as a setting of Mercury (obv. 8), and the positions of Mars (obv. 9), agree with this date.

X202112.date_comments: The date is based on the mention of a king Antiochus and of a position of Saturn in rev. 9'. It is confirmed by the goal-year text LBAT *1237 which lists "13 4,40 ŠÚ" and "14 11 na "corresponding to rev. 10'f.

X202121.date_comments: Only texts from the Seleucid era indicate the time when a planet entered a zodiacal sign (rev. 9). In obv. 8', an acronychal rising of Sirius is mentioned for the 13th. According to the scheme used for the phenomena of Sirius, this identifies the year as SE 4 plus a multiple of 19. Additional information for dating are a conjunction of Jupiter with θ Ophiuchi (rev. 5) on the 28th, and Mars in Virgo (lower edge 1, rev. 10). This fixes the date as SE 99. It is confirmed by Venus’ entry into Sagittarius on the 9th (rev. 9) and by the lunar data.

X202130.date_comments: The following conditions must be fulfilled: (a) there is a king Antiochus; (b) Jupiter is above α Librae in the last part of the night; (c) on the 24th of the same month, the moon is 1 cubit above and ½ cubit to the west of α Librae. Only SE 98 VIII fits all these conditions. The remaining lunar data agree with this date

X202180.copy: LBAT 292 (35110), 293 (45725); 45995 is listed as LBAT *238 under a wrong date.

X202250.text_comments: Star names are frequently abbreviated in this text.

X202262.text_comments: Obv. Broken except for the word sin "moon" in one place. Rev. 6': The star reappearing from behind the moon is β Tauri. Rev. 9': For BE in eclipse statements see ACT p. 162f.

X202270.date_comments: Part of the year number is preserved on the left edge. Comparison of lunar data on obverse and reverse shows that only one month is involved in the fragment remaining of this diary. The positions of the moon within the month with which the diary deals (and the weather) show that it is around the end of the year (XI to I). About the 17th or 18th, the moon was next to Saturn (rev. 3'). In combination with the expected occultations of η Tauri (obv. 3') and β Tauri (obv. 4'), this gives a date of SE 84 XI. A solar eclipse (rev. 12') is described as if it was observed; unfortunately, the one occurring in SE 84 XI was not visible in Babylon. Since the other years containing 24 are ruled out by the above data, one will have to assume that the wording of the solar eclipse statement is an exception to the rule (such exceptions do occur)

X202291.date_comments: The date of this fragment is based on: a) an acronychal rising of Mars on the 19th in Virgo or Leo (obv. 5' and rev. 5); b) Jupiter in Gemini (note that Gemini is written with only one MAŠ sign); c) Venus in Pisces or Aries; d) Mercury in Aquarius. The only possible date is SE 82 XI. Unfortunately, the few entries preserved for this month in B (see below) are not all in agreement with what is contained in this fragment.

X202292.date_comments: Mention of a king Seleucus (obv. 10') shows the fragment to be from the Seleucid era. The date is then found from: Jupiter in Gemini (rev. 12'); Saturn next to γ Virginis (rev. 3'); solar eclipse omitted (rev. 10'); a stationary point of some outer planet (rev. 11') fits Mars.

X202300.tablet_comments: All three pieces are parts of the same tablet. They will be presented in chronological order.

X202320.text_comments: Obv. 36: date of solstice restored according to scheme

X202340.tablet_comments: Both fragments are almost certainly part of the same tablet; the first line of B goes together with line 23 of A. Line numbering in this edition is therefore continuous.
X202340.text_comments: Obv. 25: "Night of the 7th" is to be restored here because the daytime part of the 7th follows. However, the moon was next to β (or α ) Arietis only on the 8th. Rev. 8': No planet can appear 3 cubits below α Coronae; the object here must be a comet or the like. If so, one would expect a reference to the direction of its tail (cf. the observations of Halley's comet in Babylonian diaries, see F.R.Stephenson and C.B.F.Walker, Halley's Comet in History, p.17ff.); I am not sure about the reading and meaning of TE-šú here. Cf. TE HAB-rat in No. -209D rev. 12.

X202380.date_comments: From the description the eclipse can be identified with certainty.

X202390.date_comments: The date is based on the following observations: Jupiter was in Leo (obv. 3'). Since Jupiter does not move very fast, it can be assumed to be in Leo or not far from it also at the time to which the reverse of the tablet refers. According to rev. 3', the moon (no other planet is available) was above Saturn and at the same time behind Mars, so Saturn was a small distance to the east of Mars. Shortly thereafter, Jupiter is said to be in retrograde motion (rev. 6'). In obv. 6', the moon is 1 ½ cubits west of Mars not long after the beginning of a month.

X202400.date_comments: The date can be easily established by several planetary observations and the mention of a solar eclipse (obv. 3').

X202410.date_comments: The following information suffices to establish the date: a) first appearance of Jupiter around the 16th in the end of Taurus; at the end of the month, Jupiter was in Gemini; b) a solar eclipse (not total) at the end of the month; c) first appearance of Mercury in the east in Gemini, 1 cubit to the east of Jupiter. Other observations in the text agree with this date

X202420.date_comments: Portions of two consecutive months are preserved. On the 27th of the first month, "the moon was 1+[x] cubits above δ Capricorni, 1 ½ cubits above Mercury, the moon being ½ cubit back to the west" (obv. 11'). Between -400 and 0, the longitude of δ Capricorni fell between 290° and 295°. Therefore the conjunction of sun and moon at the end of this month must have occurred at a longitude greater than 300°. The text indicates that the month had 30 days. Conjunction must have occurred on the 29th. At the beginning of the following month, the longitude of the sun was therefore approximately between 314° and 338°. This second month can then have been only XI or XII. In the summary at the end of the first month, Jupiter is reported to be in Taurus; furthermore, between the 2nd and the 7th of the second month, "the moon was 2 cubits behind η Tauri, 2 2/3 cubits behind Jupiter to the east" (rev. 4). Hence the longitude of Jupiter at the beginning of the second month was between 28° and 32°. If this is combined with the Mercury data of the 27th of the first month, the only possible date remaining is SE 69, months XI and XII. Once this date is found, the planet which began month XI in Libra according to the statement in rev. 1 turns out to be Mars, which moved from ca. 195° to 206° during month XI.

X202451.tablet_comments: BM 132276 formerly belonged to the Chappelow Collection. The join between the two fragments, one in Paris and one in London, is based on photographs only, but nevertheless certain. The two exemplars are presented in chronological order.

X202470.tablet_comments: All fragments are probably parts of the same tablet. The two parts of C do not quite join, but are certainly from the same tablet. The fragments will be presented in chronological order.

X202480.date_comments: Based on the following considerations: a) A partial solar eclipse is mentioned in obv. 8'f.; its time is preserved: 90° before or after sunset, so it must have occurred around noon. b) On the 20th of a month, the moon was in front of β Capricorni; on a preceding day, the moon was 1 ½ cubits behind Saturn (obv. 5'). It is certain that the observation with Saturn concerned the moon because the expression "stood to the east/west" is used only of the moon in relation to planets. It is also certain that the immediately preceding day, i.e. the 19th, is to be restored because there is only one Normal star between θ Ophiuchi (mentioned in obv. 4') and γ Capricorni, viz. β Capricorni, which is about 17 ½° "before" γ Capricorni; so the moon must have passed it somewhat more than a day earlier. Saturn is therefore to be sought not far from β Capricorni. c) On the 17th of the same month, Venus, being morning star, was below η Piscium (obv. 4'). The Mercury observation in obv. 2' agrees with the date thus found. The statement about Jupiter in rev. 3' does not fit, however; Jupiter was invisible during almost all of month VII. One could explain this as an error for Mercury which moved from Virgo into Libra in the course of this month. Note that a first appearance of a planet is observed in rev. 5'; this would refer to Jupiter.

X202491.text_comments: 10': The traces before MÁŠ suggest the restoration [S]I. This would lead to further restoration of the date as GE6 11; the distance from the moon to β Capricorni at the beginning of the night is however about 6°, much more than 1 cubit 8 fingers. From this point of view, one of the stars of SUHUR MÁŠ, and consequently a date of GE6 12, would fit better; but the traces of the sign before MÁŠ do not support this.
X202491.date_comments: The date is based on the following considerations: a) mention of a city Antuki[...], i.e., Antioch (l. 6'); b) second stationary point of Saturn around the 29th of a month which is not the last of the year (l. 3'); c) last appearance of Mars during the same month (l. 5'; the restoration of Mars is certain because it is always mentioned last in the planetary summaries); d) on the 9th of the following month, the moon was below Saturn (l. 9'); e) between the 9th and the 16th of this second month, Venus was below α Librae (l. 10').

X202492.date_comments: The date is based on: a) first appearance of Saturn in the beginning of Capricorn on the 26th of some month (obv. 5'); b) on the same day, Mars was 2/3 cubit to the west of Saturn; c) on the 20th of the same month, first appearance of Mercury in the west in Capricorn (obv. 3'); d) on the 24th, Venus is about 8 fingers behind θ Ophiuchi (obv. 4')

X202510.text_comments: Obv. 4: In LBAT 1214 i 4 the sum of ME and GE6 is given as 6,30; since ME = 4,10 is listed in line 3, 2,20 can be restored here. Upper edge 2: the phrase elēnu apātu ša mīl kiššati also occurs in LBAT 950:3'.  UE 3: -ke- is written like ku.
X202510.bibilography: A translation by A. Sachs was published apud A. Aaboe, Centaurus 24 (1980) 17ff.

X202530.tablet_comments: Both pieces are part of the same tablet.
X202530.text_comments: A1 7,B1 3': B1 seems to give a slightly different position of the moon relative to γ Virginis on the 25th by adding a distance of 2 fingers (above or below).

X202540.text_comments: Rev. 11f.: Solar eclipse of -254 Sep. 6. Left edge: note that only the sign EN "until" is preserved.

X202560.tablet_comments: Both pieces are parts of the same tablet and can almost be joined.
X202560.months_recorded: I II III IV [ ] XI XII [

X202600.text_comments: Obv. 1: If the lunar observation in this line refers to the night of the 1st day, then month I began a day later than given in PD.
X202600.date_comments: Two kings named Antiochus, of whom the older one is called "great king", are attested only for years 46 to 51 of the Seleucid era. In rev. 4' an observation of the moon 3 cubits west of α Virginis is combined with the information that the moon was below Saturn. Saturn is in an appropriate position only in year 51, month VI. This date is corroborated by rev. 7', where a phase of Mercury in the east on the 22nd in the beginning of Libra is mentioned. In rev. 3', a planet is said to have been above θ Ophiuchi (the moon is excluded because of its position given in the following line); Mars is exactly in the place required. The obverse fits month I of the same year if one assumes that the month began one day later than computed in PD

X300600.date_comments: The season, late fall, can be estimated from the lunar positions. An acronychal rising of Saturn on the 29th (rev. 6) must then have occurred in Aries, Taurus, or Gemini. There was a first appearance in the east of Mercury on the 23rd (rev. 4) and a corresponding last appearance in the west in Scorpius on the 7th (l. 5´). Jupiter, visible in the morning, was near a Normal star on the 6th (l. 4´). Venus, being morning star, was near α Librae on the 25th; at the same time, the moon was 1 cubit below Venus (rev. 5). Together these conditions determine the date.

X300620.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period; a queen Teleunike (l. 1) is attested in the first half of the 1st century BC. A lunar eclipse was considered unobservable because it occurred after sunrise (l. 7); a solar eclipse at the end of the same month was expected but could not be seen (l. 12). Venus was evening star (l. 8).

X300630.text_comments: 2´: Jupiter or Mercury can be restored here.
X300630.date_comments: Last appearances of Mercury and Mars are recorded with day numbers. The position of Venus can be found approximately from its relation to the moon. The moon’s position indicates the season. The only possible date is SE 248 III.

X300720.date_comments: The ‘citizens’ (l. 9´) occur for the first time in SE 140. In the second of the two months covered, there was a partial lunar eclipse in Taurus about two hours before sunrise (l. 16´ff.). On the 5th of the same month, Mars had a last appearance (l. 13´). On the 18th of the preceding month, Venus moved into Sagittarius (l. 3´). The only possible date is SE 239 VIII/IX. This result was also reached by F. R. Stephenson. In the beginning of l. 3´, the traces could be restored to Saturn in agreement with computation. However, this violates the normal order of planets. A restoration Jupiter complies with this order but is against computation.

X300730.date_comments: River level statements with na occur only in the Seleucid era. A solstice on the 8th (l. 8´) determines the year modulo 19. The date SE 238 can be fixed by the planetary summary (l. 15´f.).

X300760.date_comments: During a partial lunar eclipse, Jupiter and Sirius were visible. A few days before, Mars was below β Capricorni; again a few days earlier, Venus was below β Capricorni.

X300771.tablet_comments: The beginning of the obverse is badly preserved. While for the astronomical part guesses can be made, the historical notes in lines 8-12 are hopeless to me.
X300771.copy: ADART III, plate 293 (parts of 45689, by Pinches); listed as LBAT *514 (45689)
X300771.text_comments: 34´: Venus was near β /ζ Tauri at this time. Rev. 6: for ina KALAG, which refers to possible sightings of the lunar crescent on the 30th day, see Kugler, SSB II 536f. and 478 ad 11. Left edge: Restored from LBAT 1162+1163 r. 10.

X300772.text_comments: 29´: δ Capricorni was due for an occultation by the moon. Rev. 13´: The form Qabinaškiri comes closer to the assumed Elamite term kabneškir, see W. B. Henning, Asia Major 2 (1952) 164ff.
X300772.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period (l. 11´). The date can be found from the planetary summaries in l. 10´, 25´f., and rev.12´.

X300780.date_comments: The season is fall, as can be seen from the lunar positions. Jupiter was in Aquarius; Mercury had a last appearance which was omitted before the 11th. Towards the end of the month, Venus was in the end of Scorpius. On the 27th, the moon was near α Virginis. These conditions fit only SE 233 VI.

X300800.text_comments: 7´: ŠÚ.ŠÚ-AŠ may mean some light cloud cover or haze; a halo is mentioned after it.
X300800.date_comments: A total lunar eclipse occurred in the beginning of Scorpius ca. 4 hours after sunset. On the 7th of the same month, Mars was near ζ Tauri.

X300821.copy: ADART III, plate 288 (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •510

X300822.copy: ADART III, plate 289 (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •511
X300822.text_comments: Rev. 15´: According to computation, the moon was to the west (i.e., in front) of Mars.
X300822.date_comments: The ‘citizens’ occur only after SE 140. By means of the planetary positions the text can be dated securely to SE 229.

X300830.copy: ADART III, plate 286 (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •509
X300830.date_comments: The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (l. 23´). A solstice on the 18th (l. 15´) can according to the scheme only be a summer solstice; the month is III, and the year is SE 0 + 19n. The planetary observations determine the year as SE 228.

X300851.date_comments: The date is based on three observations: Jupiter at the end of the month above δ Cancri; Mars on the 21st below γ Virginis; Mercury, on the 16th or 17th, below α Geminorum. The lunar positions decide for SE 226 II.

X300852.text_comments: 10´: The ziqpu star observation probably served to fix the time of a close approach or an occultation by the moon of α Tauri.
X300852.date_comments: This text was dated by F. R. Stephenson who realized that the observation in l. 10´ need not refer to a lunar eclipse, but could imply a close approach or an occultation.

X300853.tablet_comments: The two fragments are parts of the same tablet but do not join.
X300853.date_comments: An acronychal rising of Sirius on the 6th (rev. 1) identifies the month as X and the year as SE 17 + 19n. The year can then be found from the planetary summary in rev. 13.

X300861.bibilography: Previous edition: F. R. Stephenson and C. B. F. Walker (eds.), Halley’s Comet in History (London 1985), p. 39f.
X300861.date_comments: The mention of Seleucia excludes dates before the 3rd century BC. The following can be said about the reverse: Around the 4th, Mercury set in the east in Leo; on the 3rd, the moon was 4° east of Venus, the latter therefore being evening star. Between 13th and 19th, Venus was below α Librae. Between the 4th and the 12th, Mars was 6 fingers above δ Cancri. The only date which fits all these conditions is SE 225 V.

X300862.tablet_comments: Flake'. Formerly in the Chappelow Collection
X300862.date_comments: The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (l. 10´). The season of the year can be inferred from the moon’s positions. Early in the month, Mars was above β Virginis (l. 13´). A first appearance of Mercury in the east in the beginning of Scorpius occurred around the turn of the month (l. 12´); Venus disappeared after the 18th and was due to reappear on the 24th in Sagittarius. The date thus found, SE 225 VIII, can be confirmed by the remaining data.

X300871.copy: ADART III, plate 281f. (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •501f.
X300871.date_comments: River level statements with na begin only in the Seleucid era. The text can then be dated by means of the planetary summary (rev. 13´) and several other planetary positions.

X300873.tablet_comments: 41921 is the (non-joining) lower right corner of the tablet.
X300873.copy: ADART III, plate 282 (41921, by Pinches); listed as LBAT *504, *505, •506
X300873.text_comments: 18´ff.: Eclipse of -86 Feb 28/Mar 1. 19´: Sirius is probably to be restored after Saturn. 31´: this line supports the proposal of G. McEwan in Iran 24 (1986) 92f., to see in ša iṭṭarridu an expression for a second name of a king. 33´: First appearance of Venus in the west is also recorded for the 29th of the preceding month in line 28´.

X300900.tablet_comments: The BM 132278 component was formerly in the Chappelow Collection. Thanks to the cooperation of E. Sollberger and K. R. Veenhof, the piece from the Böhl Collection in Leiden was joined to the British Museum fragments for a few hours on June 29, 1963 in London so that photographs could be made.
X300900.copy: ADART III, plate 278f. (41529 and 41546; by Pinches); listed as LBAT •495 (41529), •496 (41546) and •497 (Böhl 1332)

X300931.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period (rev. 23). The date can be easily established from the many planetary observations.

X300940.date_comments: River level statements with na (l. 4´) begin only in the Seleucid era. A month name is preserved in l. 5´. Several observations of Venus as evening star, a last appearance of Mercury in the east which did not actually occur (l. 9´), and a position of Mars (l. 13´) determine the date as SE 217.

X300952.date_comments: Statements about planets reaching zodiacal signs (l.12´) occur only in the Seleucid era. A second stationary point of Jupiter in front of β Virginis occurred in SE 133, 216 and 228; Mars reaching Gemini (l. 12´) and Mercury below η Tauri (l. 2´) decide for SE 216 I.

X300953.text_comments: 8´: The phenomenon expected could have been a last appearance of Venus. Rev. 12´: This may refer to Armenia, which usually has the city determinative before its name.
X300953.date_comments: River level statements with na begin only in the Seleucid period (l. 4´). The lunar positions on the reverse indicate the middle of the Babylonian year (months V to VII). There was a first appearance of Mercury in the east on the 16th (or slightly before) in the end of Leo. On the 16th, there was also an acronychal rising of Saturn (rev. 3´). An occultation of Venus in Leo on the 26th was considered likely (rev. 6´). Some months earlier (obv. 3´), Mars had been in Taurus.

X300954.copy: ADART III, plate 283 (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •512
X300954.date_comments: The mention of Tigranes makes a date at the end of the 2nd century or in the first half of the 1st likely. The lunar positions show the season to be spring; an exact lunar position is recorded for the first evening of a month which is not the first of the year, i.e., either II or III (l. 12´). Based on this, a lunar position just before the 7th (l. 14´) has to be above or below some other body because the other coordinate is expressed by ‘the moon having passed a little to the east’. No suitable star can be reconciled with the traces, but they do fit Jupiter. According to the order in which the planets are listed in planetary summaries, Mars is most likely to be restored in l. 8´. On the 28th of the preceding month, a rising or setting of Mercury in the east was omitted. These conditions together cannot be fulfilled in any year of the period in question. It it however likely that the decision about a Mercury phenomenon to have been omitted was made by the Babylonian astronomers by criteria different from our modern ones. If one extends the possible dates to those years in which a Mercury phenomenon occurred at the time indicated in the text, SE 216 III emerges as a solution. Some phenomenon on the 21st of the preceding month (l. 4´) turns out to be a last appearance of Sirius. Confirmation comes from the price of wool (l. 8´), which agrees with that in SE 216 I.

X300955.date_comments: The date is based on the lunar eclipse in Aquarius (l. 7´f.) and a last appearance in the west of Mercury in Virgo (l. 10´).

X300956.date_comments: Venus, being morning star, was 3 ½ cubits below β Geminorum on the 15th; before that, there was a lunar eclipse for which a culminating point is indicated. In addition, a solar eclipse was considered possible at the end of the same month. These data fit only SE 216 V.

X300961.date_comments: The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (l. 13´). The date can then be determined uniquely by the planetary summary (l. 10´f.).

X300962.text_comments: 16´: π Scorpii was occulted by the moon on VI 4.
X300962.date_comments: The date is based on the following observations: Mars was in Aquarius (l. 14´); Jupiter had a first appearance on the 24th in Virgo (l. 10´); a lunar eclipse passed by on the 14th (l. 4´).

X300963.date_comments: River level statements with na begin only in the Seleucid period (l. 5´). From the position of Saturn relative to the moon (l. 8´) it can be found that Saturn was in the end of Aquarius or beginning of Pisces. On the 29th of the following month, Mars was below ηTauri (rev. 12´). Between the 9th and 13th of the same month, Venus was near η Piscium (rev. 4´).

X300970.text_comments: Rev. 5: if the restoration of the moon´s position is correct, month V 0 is -97 Aug 11/12, different from PD (-97 Aug 12/13). There is no other evidence preserved to decide the matter.

X300991.date_comments: Jupiter was in Gemini, and Venus moved from Scorpius into Sagittarius (l. 8´). In the beginning of the following month, Mercury had a first appearance in the east in Libra (l. 11´). Finally, a solar eclipse was possible on the 28th. These data fit only SE 212 VII.

X300992.text_comments: 18´: ina IGI ... ana ŠÚ error for ár ... ana NIM.
X300992.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period (l. 15´). In a month which was neither the last nor the first of the year, Jupiter was in Taurus (l. 14´); on the 25th, Mars was above α Librae (l. 12´). There was also a last appearance of Mercury on 10th of the same month (l. 5´f.). The date SE 212 IX can be confirmed by the lunar data.

X300993.tablet_comments: This text consists of excerpts from astronomical diaries, but it is far from clear why this particular selection of data was made. The close approaches of pairs of planets are systematically reported, as are the three lunar eclipses. The period covered, more than a year, is highly unusual. Detailed comparison with the diaries written at Babylon reveals a number of startling contrasts. The terminology includes some elements which never appear at Babylon, e.g., the mention of the zodiacal sign when eclipses or close approaches of planets are recorded. It is therefore unlikely that the text comes from Babylon. Uruk is a possible provenience.
X300993.text_comments: Obv. 4: The tablet has 2 ME 14 erroneously.

X301031.date_comments: Statements about planets reaching zodiacal signs (l. 12´) occur only in the Seleucid era. There was a first appearance of Venus in the east in Taurus on the 14th (l. 8´) and a corresponding last appearance on the 6th (l. 3´). Together with the data on Mercury (l. 12´) this allows to determine the date as SE 208 II.

X301032.date_comments: The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (rev. 2´). A solstice on the 13th (l. 12´), possible in months III or IX, can be identified as winter solstice by the weather; this determines the year modulo 19. A first appearance of Saturn on the 6th in Sagittarius decides for SE 208. This is confirmed by Jupiter near the moon on the 2nd day.

X301040.date_comments: On the 5th, the positions of Jupiter and Saturn relative to θ Ophiuchi can be estimated because of the observations of the moon in relation to both planets and the star. In addition, Mars was below α Librae on this night. The only possible date is SE 207 VI.

X301051.tablet_comments: The two tablets are partial duplicates and are presented in parallel.
X301051.text_comments: A14´: For repairs in Esangila in this period see F. Joannès, Orient-Express 1991-1 p. 11. A rev. 25´: tabarān seems to be the same as tabalān "thieves" here.
X301051.date_comments: Exemplar B is clearly a duplicate of A, in spite of occasional deviations in numbers. The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (rev. 22´); its date can be easily found from the numerous observations.

X301060.date_comments: A total lunar eclipse occurred on the 14th or 15th, at 66° after sunset, the moon being near γ Virginis. The time of the year can be estimated from the lunar positions. The only eclipse fitting is that of -105 Feb 28/Mar 1. This date was found by F. R. Stephenson.

X301071.date_comments: The type of river level statement shows the text to be from the Seleucid era. The lunar positions can be restored; from them it appears that Mars was in Taurus (l. 7), Saturn in Libra, and Mercury in Leo. In addition, Mercury had a last appearance in the west on the 18th. This reduces the possibilities to a few; exact computation shows only SE 204 to be possible.

X301073.text_comments: Rev. 2´: The passage about disease is again found in rev. 21´. The damaged sign is not unlike LUGAL "king", but longer. 7´: na abbreviation for nalšu ?

X301074.tablet_comments: The three pieces are parts of the same tablet.

X301081.tablet_comments: The two tablets duplicate each other and are presented in parallel.

X301083.date_comments: The first month preserved is VI (VII is still visible in l. 13´). On the 24th, the moon was 2 cubits in front of Jupiter; taken together with the surrounding lunar positions, Jupiter’s longitude must have been between 140° and 150°. On VI 27, Venus came close to β Virginis. These conditions are fulfilled only in SE 203.

X301091.date_comments: A total lunar eclipse occurred near α Tauri; not all the planets were visible during the eclipse. In addition, there was a first stationary point of Jupiter near α Leonis around the 26th, and a first appearance of Venus in the west in Scorpius around the 11th.

X301092.date_comments: The text was written after the founding of Seleucia (l. 7´). According to the planetary summary in l. 5´, Saturn was in Libra, and Mars in Taurus. One planet was invisible; another one was in Sagittarius towards the end of the month. This places the date at SE 202 VIII.

X301100.text_comments: 1´: If correctly restored, this is the earliest occurrence of the title "king of kings" (so far attested only from SE 204 on, see J. Oelsner, Materialien zur babylonischen Gesellschaft und Kultur in hellenistischer Zeit, p. 311 n. 116. 9´: The signs in {} were erased by the scribe.
X301100.date_comments: The epithet ‘king of kings’ is used only by Arsacid kings. In a month which is not the last of the year, Saturn had a last appearance in Virgo (l. 12´). During the same month, Mercury appeared and disappeared in Virgo on the 4th and 27th, respectively. On the 26th, Venus was below β Librae. This suffices to determine the date.

X301112.text_comments: Rev. 7´: Red river water is also reported in No. -77A r. 29; both passages refer to a very low water level.
X301112.date_comments: Seleucia is mentioned (rev. 8´). The year can be determined modulo 19 by a solstice on the 8th (l. 12´). On the 1st of a month which was not the first of the year, Saturn had a last appearance in Virgo (rev. 13´). On the 10th of the same month, Venus as morning star was in conjunction with ε Leonis (rev. 16´).

X301113.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period (l. 4´). Its date can then be found from the planetary summary (l. 3´).

X301114.tablet_comments: Both fragments are part of the same tablet, but cannot be joined. Line 1´ of D2 is continued by line 8´ of D1.
X301114.date_comments: A lunar eclipse was omitted (l. 5´); not long before, α Scorpii was occulted by the moon (l. 4´). Jupiter and Venus were in Taurus. During the month, Venus moved into Gemini; between 16th and 18th, she was 1 cubit below ζ Tauri (l. 7´). These data are compatible only with SE 200 III.

X301120.date_comments: The tablet is later than the founding of Seleucia (l. 16). The month VII is preserved on the obverse. Saturn and Mars were in Virgo; Mars moved into Libra (l. 13). Before the 9th, a first appearance of Mercury in the west was omitted (l. 3). This suffices to determine the date.

X301171.date_comments: River level statements using the na gauge begin at the end of the 4th century. In a month which was not the last of the year, Jupiter had a first appearance around the 23rd in Scorpius, and Venus had a first appearance in the west around the 17th in the end of Scorpius. On the 2nd of the following month, the moon was near β Capricorni; this determines the season. The only possible date SE 194 VIII is confirmed by the lunar positions.

X301172.date_comments: Statements about the planets reaching a zodiacal sign (rev. 4´) begin only in the Seleucid period. A second stationary point of Saturn occurred around the 6th near α Geminorum (rev. 9´). During the same month, Mars moved from Pisces into Aries (rev. 19´). A solar eclipse possibility five months after another one (rev. 17´) then allows us to determine the date. The other observations, like a last appearance of Mercury in the east (rev. 13´), confirm it.

X301181.tablet_comments: This tablet deteriorated in some places since Pinches copied it. The two exemplars have the same date and are transliterated in parallel.
X301181.copy: ADART III, plate 249-251 (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •459

X301191.tablet_comments: These two pieces are certainly part of one tablet. Since exemplars A, B, and C are partial duplicates, their transliterations are presented in parallel.

X301194.tablet_comments: Date uncertain; the first line fits SE 192 or SE 250.
X301194.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period. Around the middle of the month, the moon was behind θ Ophiuchi (l. 13); this indicates that we are in the beginning of the Babylonian year, most likely month I. At its first visibility, the moon was 1? cubit in front of Saturn (l. 1); this fits either SE 192 or SE 250.

X301200.date_comments: A unique solution can be found from the planetary summary in rev. 4´; it is confirmed by the remaining observations.

X301210.tablet_comments: Both fragments are part of the same tablet; obv. 1´ of BM 34827 is continued by obv. 4´ of BM 35635.
X301210.date_comments: On the 9th of a month which was not the first of the year, Jupiter had a first appearance in Cancer (l. 9´). On the 16th of the same month, towards morning, Saturn was below η Tauri; some night between the 16th and the 18th, Mars was below γ Virginis (l. 11´). Only SE 190 IV fits. This date is confirmed by other, fragmentary observations of planets.

X301221.date_comments: The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (l. 6´). The lunar positions indicate the season to be spring. On the 2nd day of a month which was not the first of the year, the moon was below ζ Tauri and also below Jupiter; hence Jupiter had a longitude of ca. 55° (l. 9´). On the 4th of the same month, Mercury had a last appearance in the west in Taurus (l 10´). Later, Jupiter is below α Geminorum (rev. 4´). According to F. R. Stephenson, only SE 189 fits these conditions. The lunar observations can then be restored and confirm the date.

X301222.tablet_comments: The reverse can be partly restored from exemplar D obv.
X301222.text_comments: Rev. 1´: Venus was near α Geminorum at this time, but the traces do not fit.
X301222.date_comments: The statements about planets reaching zodiacal signs (l. 11´) became customary only in the Seleucid period. In this year there was a lunar eclipse (rev. 6´). Earlier in the year, Venus as morning star was below α Arietis on the 25th of a month (l. 7´); on the 7th of the same month, Mars reached Aries. This determines the date as SE 189.

X301223.date_comments: On the 25th of a month which was neither the first nor the last of the year, Venus as morning star came close to Jupiter (rev. 9); this happened a few days after Venus had been close to μ Geminorum (rev. 7). Lunar positions indicate the season. In the preceding month, Mercury was observed just on the 24th and 25th in Gemini (l. 10´f.). On the 15th of this month, Venus was close to η Tauri (l. 7´). Between the 2nd and 4th of this month, Mars was close to some star or planet (l. 4´); after the date SE 189 is found from the other observations, this turns out to be Saturn.

X301224.text_comments: Obv. 10´: The star is probably ι Aquarii whose longitude is ca. 5° more than that of δ Capricorni. Rev. 10´: The reading of L[Ú.N]E is uncertain; one would expect something like aššu before it: "because of hostility".
X301224.date_comments: Statements about planets reaching zodiacal signs are attested only from the Seleucid period on (rev. 8´). The planetary summary (rev. 8´f.) suffices to determine the date; it can be independently confirmed by a partial lunar eclipse (l. 8´ff.).

X301225.text_comments: Obv. 4´: Only first appearances of Mercury take place during the time in question: in month VIII in the west and in month IX in the east. The translation depends on which one is referred to here. Rev. 3´: Cf. LBAT 1055:32: 13 2,20 na. Rev. 7´: Cf. LBAT 1055:30f.: 18 USAN AN e MÚL IGI šá ALLA šá SI 2 SI. Rev. 8´: Cf. LBAT 1055:33f.: 24 USAN MÚL.BABBAR SIG MAŠ.MAŠ IGI 4 KÙŠ. Rev. 10´: Cf. LBAT 1055:35: 28 USAN AN e MÚL ár šá ALLA šá ULÙ 20 SI.
X301225.date_comments: River level statements with na begin only at the end of the 4th century (rev. 14´). The date can be found from a last appearance of Saturn on the 19th (rev. 13´); Mars in conjunction with η Cancri on the 22nd (rev. 7´); Jupiter in conjunction with α Geminorum on the 24th (rev. 8´). This fits only SE 189 XII. The date is confirmed by LBAT 1055, which deals with the same year.

X301231.text_comments: Obv. 18´: The same epithet of Hyspaosines probably occurs in No. -132B rev. 19. Rev. 3: Solar eclipse of -123 July 29 (not visible in Babylon). 14f.: Lunar eclipse of -123 Aug 13.
X301231.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period (l. 18ff.). A well-described total lunar eclipse occurred in month V (rev. 14f.); in addition, numerous planetary positions are recorded. The date can only be SE 188.

X301232.text_comments: 11´: According to computation, Venus was below β Scorpii.
X301232.date_comments: A satrap is mentioned (l. 15´), so the text is from Achaemenid times or later; writing suggests a later date. An equinox is listed for the 28th; the lunar positions show the season to be autumn, and the equinox to fall on VI 28. According to the scheme the year is then SE 17 + 19n. The statements about Saturn and Mars (l. 14´) determine the date.

X301233.date_comments: The text concerns a year after the founding of Seleucia (l. 15´). A total lunar eclipse occurred in a month which was not the last of the year (l. 4´f.). During the first half of the eclipse, Mercury and Venus set. On the 23rd of the same month, Venus reached Libra (l. 11´); on the 1st of the following month, Mercury was close to disappearance (l. 18´); accordingly, a first appearance of Mercury can be restored for the 10th of the earlier month (l. 11´). These conditions fit only SE 188.

X301241.text_comments: 9´: cf. rev. 7´. 10´: According to the scheme for Sirius dates, the last visibility should be expected for I 30 instead of II 1; but the preceding month had only 29 days.
X301241.date_comments: Both texts can be easily dated from their numerous observations.
X301241.months_recorded: I II III IV V VI

X301242.copy: ADART III, plate 236f. (45693, by Pinches); listed as LBAT •450 and •451
X301242.text_comments: 18´: Mercury reached Aquarius around the 25th; the sign is not GU, however. 19´: da-kil-tú, if read correctly, could be dakištu which refers to a part of a city in Old Bab. mathematical texts, cf. AHw. p. 1549b. 20´: UŠ4 occurs once in Late Babylonian according to von Soden, Das akkadische Syllabar, No. 290b; using this reading here, a verbal form fitting the context is produced. Admittedly, a passive Št-stem of wabālu is so far attested only in Old Assyrian. Rev. 18: restore possibly ina ka[kki ušam]qit.
X301242.date_comments: Both texts can be easily dated from their numerous observations.

X301251.copy: ADART III, plate 235f. (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •447
X301251.text_comments: 1: The moon was to the east of Mars on the 4th, but the distance was about 10°, much more than 2 cubits. The traces before this statement look like GUB, but this expression is used to describe the relation of the moon to planets, and no planet other than Mars is near the moon on this night. 12: maššaltu ‘sieve’ is unlikely here. 13: The expression ṭibih ṣupri, literally ‘slaughtering of a (finger)nail’ is not attested elsewhere; I did not, however, find a different reading. It seems to be a weather phenomenon. SI here and in the following line may be part of a building; is it to be read qarnu, qannu ‘edge, fringe’ ? 14: Since the beginning of the line is damaged, I do not know whether ‘servant of Marduk’ refers to a person mentioned before. According to the writing conventions of these texts, LÚ.TUR Marduk could also mean ‘son of Marduk’. - aburru seems to be part of a building here. - I take A.GURMEŠ to be a plural of agurru ‘baked brick’. At the end of the line read probably ESIR.HI.A. 17: It is unlikely that Aspasinē is to be restored at the beginning. The feminine form of ṭarādu which follows most likely refers to a water course whose name ended in -nē. The verb ṭarādu here is probably the one meaning ‘to name, call’, see G. McEwan, Iran 24 (1986) 92f. - Most of this line remains obscure. 18: Instead of ‘threw’, one could as well translate ‘fell’. Rev. 17´: Solar eclipse of -125 Sep 19.
X301251.date_comments: A year 185 is mentioned (l. 20), so the text must be SE 185 or later. There was an observable solar eclipse in that year (rev. 17´); the planetary summary (l. 12) allows to determine the date as SE 186, months I to VI.

X301252.date_comments: A solar eclipse was expected on the 28th, but not observed because of clouds. On the 20th of the same month, a phenomenon of Jupiter occurred in the end of Pisces (l. 3´). On the 26th or 27th, Venus was in conjunction with η Tauri (l. 6´). This information suffices to date the text to SE 186; in l. 2´, δ Capricorni can then be restored in conjunction with Mars.

X301261.text_comments: 6´: This is probably the Greek name Timarchos.
X301261.date_comments: The text is from the Arsacid period (l. 7´). The planetary summary in l. 4´f. determines the date.

X301262.date_comments: The text concerns a month XII during the Arsacid period (l. 1). Five months earlier, a lunar eclipse had occurred (l. 15). On the 13th, the moon was 3 cubits behind β Virginis, i.e. at ca. 153°. On the 5th, some planet was in conjunction with δ Capricorni (l. 6; the moon cannot be restored here because it is in Taurus according to the preceding line). On the 17th, Mars was in conjunction with a Normal star (l. 17). All these conditions are fulfilled only in SE 185

X301291.text_comments: A1 10´f.: these lines seem to have been erased by the scribe. A1 15´: if the end of line 14 is read correctly, a (broken) line has to be assumed here to provide space for the rest of the sentence
X301291.date_comments: Date of A1: The citizens (puliṭē ) occur only after SE 140. The date can then be found from: Saturn in Capricorn, first appearance of Mars in Leo on the 9th (rev. 13´), last appearance of Mercury in the west in Virgo on the 22nd (rev. 8´), all in the same month.

X301292.date_comments: Statements about planets ‘reaching“ a zodiacal sign occur only long after the beginning of the Seleucid era. An equinox is recorded for the 22nd (l. 7´); lunar positions allow to identify it as autumnal equinox, and the month as VI. The year is therefore SE 11 + 19n. Mars reached Virgo on the 14th (l. 13´); this eliminates all dates except SE 182. The remaining observations confirm this date.

X301301.date_comments: There was a solstice on the 8th; the lunar positions show it to be summer solstice. The year is therefore SE 10 + 19n. During a lunar eclipse, Jupiter, Saturn, and Mars were visible. In addition, Saturn was near the moon shortly after the eclipse (l. 9´).

X301302.date_comments: The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (rev. 4´). A lunar eclipse occurred near β Capricorni (l. 8´). On the 10th of this month, Mars was in conjunction with δ Scorpii (l. 5´).

X301303.date_comments: na in the river level statement (l. 9´) points to the Seleucid period. Saturn was in Capricorn (l. 8´). Among the years thus identified, towards the end of a month one planet has to be in conjunction with γ Geminorum (the star is mentioned twice, so one occurrence will concern the moon, the other a planet), while a few days later another planet was in conjunction with α Scorpii. Given these conditions, only SE 181 III provides fitting restorations for the statements on the obverse, including the lunar positions. An approximately equal equivalent for dates is found in the years around SE 181. The remnants of the other side fit month IV of SE 181.

X301304.date_comments: The text is later than the founding of Seleucia (l. 18´). On the 27th of a month which was not the first of the year, Mars was in conjunction with α Tauri (rev. 19). On the 15th or 16th of the same month, Venus, being evening star, was in conjunction with η Tauri (rev. 12). In the preceding month, a last appearance of an inner planet occurred in the beginning of Pisces (l. 7´). Lunar positions (and weather) show that the last months of the Babylonian year are concerned. The date can then be determined as SE 181.

X301321.text_comments: Rev. 4´: The name at the end is restored from exemplar B r. 24.

X301322.tablet_comments: Obviously this very interesting tablet, reporting about religious and other upheavals, needs to be studied in depth. I can only stress that whatever I write here about it is to be considered preliminary and uncertain. Because of this, I have used much restraint in translating. Improved understanding will require study of the original for an extended time. The section on month VII is paralleled by exemplars C and D. Right edge: There are a few lines on the right edge, in the right part closer to the obverse; some more before them may be lost in a break. Right edge: The lower edge is written in the opposite direction from obverse and reverse; it is likely that lower edge, left edge and upper edge, in this sequence, are to be read after the end of the reverse; due to the bad state of preservation, this cannot be proved.
X301322.copy: ADART III, plate 218f. (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •438 + •439
X301322.text_comments: Obv. 8: e over erasure (of ma-šil?). 12: erasure at end of line. 16: usually, only one ‘rear star of the southern Crab’ (= δ Cancri) is taken as reference. 19: at end erasure, probably of 10 SI. Rev. 3: the restored words at the beginning of this line and at the end of line 2 may have to be distributed differently. 16: ina A is written in smaller script above the line. 17: at the beginning, 5 is rather clear, although 14 is expected (and copied by Pinches). 23: The context suggests a meaning like "he was removed" (from his position). The writing KUR URI.KI.MEŠ occurs in No. -152 rev. 14´. 24: This person (called Theodosios ?) also occurs in exemplar A r. 4´. 31: The profession (if it is one) which I have transliterated RI+ZAG is unknown to me; the signs are probably to be read differently. It occurs several times in this text, and also in exemplar C 29´. Left edge 1: a possible translation ‘the strong god who hits your gods’ is unlikely because in l. 3 māhiṣu is not followed by a noun. A few very small signs are scratched between lines 2 and 3 of the left edge.

X301323.tablet_comments: These three exemplars duplicate each other and are therefore presented in parallel transliteration. Restorations for the section on month VII are possible from another partial duplicate, exemplar B above. The translation combines these duplicating exemplars; therefore not all line numbers of the transliteration will be found in the translation.
X301323.date_comments: C can be dated from the planetary summary in l. 24f.; it also agrees so much with exemplar B that there is no doubt about its date.

X301331.date_comments: The month names are preserved. An equinox on VII 8 fixes the year as SE 7 + 19n. A solar eclipse (not necessarily visible) occurred at the end of month V, followed by a lunar one in month VI; for both, the times are given. In addition, positions of Mars (l. 7´ and rev. 9) and Jupiter (l. 13´) determine the date uniquely.

X301332.tablet_comments: Both pieces belong to the same tablet, but cannot be joined.
X301332.copy: ADART III, plate 216f. (by Pinches); listed as LBAT  •437

X301341.date_comments: A king Arsaces is mentioned, so the date must be after SE 170. The equinox in rev. 6´ identifies the month as VI and leaves only the years SE 177 + 19n for further consideration. On the 20th of the same month, Venus as evening star was above some Normal star (rev. 3´); on the 9th of the month, Mercury reached Virgo (rev. 8´). Finally, in obv. 9, the moon is said to have been near Antares, and at the same time in front of Saturn, around the middle of the month. This allows us to fix the date as SE 177.

X301342.tablet_comments: Both pieces are part of the same tablet, but do not join. B2 provides the left part of Obv. 11-24 and Rev. 1´-14´.

X301350.text_comments: Rev. 7´: LBAT 1285 r. 26 gives 13 4,30 ŠÚ. Rev. 8´: Lunar eclipse of -134 Mar 20/21.
X301350.date_comments: A lunar eclipse of ca. 4 hours length is mentioned in rev. 8´. On the 10th, Mars was almost occulted by the moon. On the 8th, a stationary point of an outer planet occurred near ρ Leonis, the planet being 1 ½ cubits above the star. These conditions are met only by SE 176 month XII. The remaining lunar observations agree with this date, which was also confirmed by F. R. Stephenson.

X301362.text_comments: Rev. 13´: The solar eclipse described in this text is also found in LBAT 1285 rev. 24ff. It was used by F.R. Stephenson to determine the slowing of the earth’s rotation.

X301363.date_comments: The text is from the Seleucid period (l. 17´). In a month which was not the last of the year, on the 25th or 26th, Jupiter was 5 cubits below α Arietis (rev. 7´); at most 3 days later, Venus was 4 cubits below α Arietis. Mercury’s movement during this month is given in rev. 11´. Finally, the approximate position of Saturn can be found from rev. 5´, where it is close to the moon. This information determines the date.

X301371.text_comments: 10´: Beginning uncertain; does UŠ mean stationary point here? 11´: MÚL.BABBAR is an error for MÚL.MÚL. Rev. 8´: Demetrius II is considered a captive of the Parthians at this time, see C. Habicht, CAH VIII 368.
X301371.date_comments: A king Arsaces occurs in rev. 10f.; the date is therefore after -140. It can be determined from the planetary statement in l. 14´, and independently confirmed by several other observations in the text.

X301372.date_comments: King Arsaces is mentioned in rev. 20´, so dates before -140 are excluded. The date is then established by the positions of Saturn in Libra and Mars in Taurus (rev. 18´), combined with a solstice on the 21st of the same month.

X301374.text_comments: Rev. 1: maṣītu for aṣītu ? 23: the end of the line will have been similar to l. 27. 25: KA-gim GAR-an for rigmu iššakkan? 26: Is GIŠ.KUR a writing for kišittu?

X301401.text_comments: 1: Restored from catch-line of No. -141 F rev. 26. 15: Beginning restored from line 18 below. Rev. 3´: Kugler misread this and translated ‘alle beliebigen Männer’, taking it as a reference to musters? by Demetrius II. - The second part of the line seems to contain the first use of the Parthian era together with the Seleucid. 4´: Urqananu may be Hyrcania rather than Arqania (below C:34), as assumed by Olmstead, Classical Philology 32 (1937) 13; but the reading is anyway uncertain. 9´: The noun qualified by ‘great’ is similar to the sign LUGAL ‘king’, but not quite identical. Some name ending in -kā may of course be Aršakā, i.e. Mithridates I; but munnû ‘appointed’ does not fit a king. 21´: Kugler read Ni-i-ka-a-(tur?) and took it to refer to Demetrius II who had assumed the title Nicator. As far as I know, Seleucid kings are never referred to by their titles in cuneiform texts; the traces of the last sign do not support Kugler´s reading; a certain Nikanor is mentioned in No. -140B r. 10, dated three months later. Upper edge 3: Instead of ina SIL.MEŠ ‘in the streets’, the signs could be read ina tar-ṣa? ‘opposite of’. 4: it is uncertain if this is the same Antiochus as mentioned above. One might guess that queen Laodike is his wife. Or does the text refer to an earlier Antiochos and his queen? 5: Kugler read Seleucia in this line, but the remaining traces do not support this.

X301402.date_comments: The text is from the Seleucid period (rev. 11). The date can be found from the planetary statements in rev. 7f.

X301403.copy: ADART III, plate 200f. (by Pinches); listed as LBAT •420
X301403.text_comments: 34: The scribe subtracted 5 units from the day number 24 at the beginning of the line instead of correctly adding 5 to 12 (the measure of water level) at the end of the preceding line.  Rev. 36´: This mention of Antiochus (VI), son of Alexander (Balas) may be important for the question of when he was murdered by Tryphon, cf. C. Habicht, CAH VIII 367.
X301403.bibilography: quoted Kugler, Von Moses bis Paulus 342.

X301404.date_comments: The mention of a general named Antiochus places the text in the Seleucid period. Its date can be found from the planetary statement in rev. 16, and it is confirmed by the other observations.

X301411.date_comments: The date can be found from the planetary summaries in l. 8´f. and 16´f.

X301412.text_comments: 7´: According to my computation, this star is σ Leonis.
X301412.date_comments: An equinox on the 4th can according to the scheme only be a vernal equinox on I 4, in years SE 18 + 19n. The planetary positions allow us to establish the year as SE 170. Moreover, data for month I preserved in both A and B agree.

X301413.date_comments: The mention of the city of Seleucia (l. 27´) leaves only dates from the 3rd century onwards. Further conditions are the zodiacal signs of Saturn and Mars (l. 10´); a stationary point of Jupiter with position indicated (l. 20´) determines the year as SE 170.

X301414.date_comments: An equinox on the 10th (l. 14´) occurs only in month VI2, i.e. every 19 years. The first appearance of Saturn (l. 9´f.) decides the matter.

X301415.date_comments: During a month which was neither the first nor the last of a year, Venus moved from Cancer into some other sign (rev. 13´). Mars was in Aries or Taurus, as can be seen from the positions of the moon when it passed Mars (rev. 9´). There was some phenomenon of Saturn during this month (rev. 14´); Saturn was in Leo or Virgo (l. 7´). Finally, a lunar eclipse which was invisible in Babylon occurred on the 14th. This determines the date as SE 170 V. The data for this month fit the incompletely preserved lines.

X301417.date_comments: Saturn in Virgo and Mars in Aries can be found more or less every 30 years. In addition, Mercury was invisible; and in the beginning of the following month, Mars had a second stationary point. Thereby the date is fixed at SE 170 VII and VIII.

X301421.text_comments: 3´: DIR AN DIB at the beginning of the line may be an erasure. 6´: for the writing KUŠ.GIL = šēnu see CAD Š/II s.v. šēnu lex. section (A III/1:244).
X301421.date_comments: The na statements about the river level point to the Seleucid period. Jupiter and Mars were in Libra; this occurs on six occasions during the period in question. The decision can be made by the lunar positions in l. 12´f. and Mars’ conjunction with β Librae (l. 5´).

X301422.text_comments: Obv. 9: ‘above’ conflicts with ‘high to the north’ in l. 11. The moon is a little bit ‘in front of’ γ Capricorni.
X301422.date_comments: The date given in LBAT is wrong; the observations in the text do not fit the computations for the date SE 170. Collation by I. L. Finkel shows the year number to be 169.

X301431.text_comments: 8´ and 14´: Restorations from LBAT 1277 r. 8. 20´: This is Antiochus VI, set up as king by the usurper Tryphon, cf. C. Habicht, CAH VIII p. 365f.
X301431.date_comments: The date can be determined from a first appearance of Sirius, which fixes the year modulo 19, and the planetary statements in l. 17´.

X301432.text_comments: 4´: Lunar eclipse of -143 Aug 25. 14´: GE6 15 error for 14.
X301432.date_comments: The months can be found from l. 11´, where the preceding month is said to be V. This line also records a first appearance of Jupiter. The approximate position of Saturn can be deduced from its conjunction with the moon in rev. 2; there is furthermore a conjunction of Saturn and Venus on the 6th. In this way the year can be identified as SE 168.

X301433.date_comments: The mention of Antioch means that no date prior to -290 needs to be considered. In the earlier of the two months preserved, Mercury was not visible. In the following month, on the 1st day, Venus (being morning star) was 1 cubit above θ Ophiuchi, i.e. at ca. 231°. On the 7th, Mars was 2 cubits east of the moon; on the next night, the moon was 20 fingers behind h Piscium, i.e. at ca. 358°. Therefore, Mars on the night before was at ca. 344°. Combining these two planetary positions yields only a few possibilities; the position of the moon and the day numbers place the date at SE 168 month IX.

X301440.tablet_comments: BM 34609 is the lower right corner of the tablet and just barely touches BM 34788+.
X301440.text_comments: 35f.: For Demetrius’ actions against Egyptian territory, see C. Habicht, CAH VIII p. 365.

X301460.text_comments: Rev. 7: Restoration of the length of the preceding month is based on the positions of moon and Venus on the first evening of month XI.
X301460.date_comments: A first appearance of Venus in the west on the 10th (l. 6´) combined with a first appearance of Mercury in the west on the 25th (rev. 5) occurs only on a few occasions. The additional condition of Jupiter being visible in the first part of the night (l. 3´) leaves only SE 165 X. The remaining data, especially a stationary point of Jupiter (rev. 3), confirm the date.

X301480.date_comments: Jupiter, not long after a stationary point in the west, was moving eastward again and below η Piscium around the 20th. On the 22nd, Mercury became visible in the east in Sagittarius. Only SE 163 IX fits these conditions. The lunar positions (l. 5´ and 7´) confirm this date.

X301491.tablet_comments: According to the curvature of the tablet, not much can be missing on top and bottom. It is therefore very likely that the events described on the reverse took place in month III. This allows to improve our knowledge of the events surrounding the defeat of Demetrius I by Alexander Balas. Demetrius seems to have been alive during most of this month which ended  July 18, -149 (= 150 BC).
X301491.copy: Listed as LBAT •400; ADART III, plate 183 (by Pinches)
X301491.text_comments: Obv. 5ff.: Lunar eclipse of -149 July 3. Rev. 7´: ‘crossed over’ may mean ‘rebelled’ or ‘defected’.
X301491.date_comments: The mention of Demetrius and Alexander, both called king, places the text in the years -151 to -149 when these two were contending for the throne of the Seleucid empire. It is then easy to determine the date of the obverse as -149 III by means of the lunar eclipse in l. 5ff.

X301492.copy: Listed as LBAT •402; ADART III, plate 184 (by Pinches)
X301492.text_comments: Rev. 10´: LÚ.NE, usually a logogram for ṣaltu "fighting", here has a plural determinative. Is it a type of troops ? The passage may refer to fighting between some troops and the people of Seleucia.
X301492.date_comments: The text is from the Seleucid period (rev. 12´) and the king was called Alexander (l. 1). The date can then be found from the planetary summary in rev. 4ff.

X301510.date_comments: An equinox occurred on the 18th or 19th. The position of the moon indicates the season; only autumn equinox is possible. According to the scheme for equinoxes, only day 19 occurs, in month VI. The equinox scheme also gives the year as SE 8 + 19n. On the 18th, Mars was visible in the evening; on the 13th, Venus was morning star. In the preceding month, Jupiter was in Sagittarius. These conditions are met only in SE 160 VI.

X301530.text_comments: Obv. 1´: Venus or Mars can be restored in the break.
X301530.date_comments: The date can be established unambiguously from the planetary positions.

X301541.date_comments: Price equivalents using "one-fourth" occur only relatively late in the Seleucid period. Then the planetary positions in l. 2´ and 4´ suffice to find the date

X301542.text_comments: 5: 29 written with 9 vertical wedges, so clearly error for 28. 118 Rev. 8´: The moon is ca. 1 ½ cubits in front of η Tauri on this evening.

X301562.date_comments: The date can be determined from a lunar eclipse (l. 6f.) and numerous planetary positions (l. 17´ and rev. 12´).

X301563.date_comments: The date can be found from the following information: Jupiter was not far from α Leonis (l. 8´); at the end of the month, it had a second stationary point. On the 15th or 16th, Saturn became visible in Aquarius (l. 12´). Venus was approaching her disappearance in the east. On the 24th, Mars was next to γ Geminorum. The lunar positions show that we are near the end of the Babylonian year.

X301571.text_comments: 2: MÚL.BABBAR seems to be written there, but according to computation no planet is above it; Venus is not far from it, but not above.
X301571.date_comments: Only one month is reported; the lunar positions suggest months III to V. Saturn was in Capricorn (l. 12); it also had an acronychal rising on the 11th. Jupiter and Mercury were in Cancer, and Venus reached Leo (rev. 12f.). This is enough to establish the date.

X301582.text_comments: 16: KÙŠ at the end of the line is most likely an error for SI

X301583.text_comments: 2´: Venus was near α Scorpii at this time
X301583.date_comments: Seleucia is mentioned (l. 7´); the date can then be easily fixed from the planetary positions in l. 5´ and 10´f., and the equinox in l. 9´.

X301585.date_comments: Seleucia is mentioned. A solstice on the 5th allows only years SE 1 + 19n, identifying the month as X (the weather shows the season not to be summer). In addition, a first appearance of Venus in the east in Capricorn (l. 4) was observed. The few remaining dates can be narrowed down to SE 153 by means of the incomplete planetary observations in l. 6 and 8

X301601.text_comments: Rev. 3´ff.: Lunar eclipse of -159 Jan 26. α Geminorum culminated when the eclipse began.
X301601.date_comments: The mention of a king Demetrius restricts the date to a few dozen years of the 2nd century BC. There was a lunar eclipse at 48° after sunset (rev. 5´). Between the 22nd and 27th of the same month, Venus was in conjunction with Jupiter (rev. 10´). The approximate position of Jupiter can be estimated from obv. 7´, where it is next to the moon on the 9th. In l. 6´, a stationary point of Jupiter in the west is expected for the 5th. Within the few years having a king Demetrius, only SE 151 is possible.

X301602.date_comments: In the first half of a month, a conjunction of Jupiter and Venus occurred (l. 3´). Around the middle of this month, the moon was in Leo (l. 5´). Later in the month, the moon was only 1 ½ cubits above α Scorpii, which has ca. -4.3° latitude (l. 9´). During this month, Mercury was visible in the last part of the night, i.e. in the east (l. 12´); one (only one) other planet was invisible (l. 13´). In a later month, Venus passes from Pisces into Aries (rev. 7´). On the 1st of the following month, some planet is 2 ½ cubits below β Capricorni. Positions of the moon show the time of the year to be between months VIII and XII. These considerations lead to SE 151.

X301603.date_comments: The na (gauge) for the river level occurs only in the Seleucid period. In some month, Jupiter was in Aries; Venus was visible (l. 1´); Mars moved from Aries to Taurus (l. 3´); Mercury had a first appearance in the west in Pisces, ca. on the 4th. The only date satisfying all conditions is SE 151 XI.

X301611.tablet_comments: All three fragments are part of the same tablet; they are here combined in transliteration and translation. Obv. 1´ of A1  corresponds to obv. 7´ of A2; rev. 1´ of A1 to rev. 15´ of A2. A3 is from the lower edge of the tablet.

X301612.text_comments: Rev. 2´: Venus or Mercury can be restored in the first part of the line.

X301613.date_comments: On the 15th of a month, Mars was near α Librae (l. 8´). From l. 12´ it can be found that Mars, being near the moon during the second half of the month, was visible in the last part of the night. On the 5th of the same month, the moon stood to the west of Jupiter. Since lunar positions on other days (l. 5´) are preserved, this allows to place Jupiter between ca. 300° and 330° longitude, being visible in the evening. These conditions determine the date.

X301631.text_comments: 1: The amount of text restored at the end of the line does not easily fit into the available space; but the damaged signs after DIR AN ZA do not look like sin ina IGI GU4.UD. The restoration itself is justified by the beginning of line 2. 11: restored from LBAT 1285:22. 14: LBAT 1285:23 gives the distance between Mercury and m Geminorum as 1 KÙŠ 4 SI. 18: restored from LBAT 1285:23. UE 4: the moon is 1 cubit behind β Scorpii on the 12th; the number 15, if read correctly, must then refer to something other than the day number.
X301631.date_comments: The date can be found from rev. 9: among the dates derived from the positions of the three visible planets, only SE 148 II has both Mars and Venus invisible. The lunar positions confirm this date.

X301632.bibilography: F. R. Stephenson and C. B. F. Walker, Halley’s Comet in History, p.21ff.
X301632.date_comments: The date of this tablet can be established from the mentioned eclipses (the solar one of -162 March 15, the lunar one of -162 March 30/31) and the numerous planetary positions. For details see Halley’s Comet in History, p. 36f.

X301633.tablet_comments: Both fragments are parts of the same tablet; their contents are arranged in chronological order
X301633.bibilography: F. R. Stephenson and C. B. F. Walker, Halley’s Comet in History, p. 28ff.
X301633.date_comments: On the 11th of some month, Saturn had a last appearance in Scorpius (l. 8´); during the same month, Mars was in Virgo. On the 11th to 13th of the following month, Venus was just 2 fingers above γ Capricorni (l. 16´). On the 11th of this same month, the moon was close to α Tauri (l. 15´). The only possible date between -500 and 0 is -163.
